{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Malolepszy et al. [89] also noted increases in compressive, split tensile, and flexural strength at a 15% replacement level.",
    "However, Jokar et al. [92] found that higher replacement levels (above 10-15%) could reduce strength.",
    "Nandhini and Karthikeyan [93] found that a 10% replacement with pulverized eggshell powder (PES) increased compressive strength by 10%, while higher replacement levels reduced strength due to stiffness and voids.",
    "Jaber et al. [95] reported that treated eggshell powder (TESP) improved compressive strength by 29% at a 15% replacement but only by 2.5% at 20%, suggesting its effectiveness at moderate levels.",
    "Maqsood and Eddie [94] observed a 1% increase in compressive strength at a 10% replacement with calcined eggshell powder (CESP) and a 17% increase at 20%, along with better flexural strength, indicating that CESP is beneficial at higher ratios."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
